{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641258"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:25:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:25:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17873"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17873"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.27,0.39,0.17,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78720"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10587"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17873"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64063"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10069"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24682"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78720"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe liver synthesises and secretes very low-density lipoproteins (VLDL) to transport triglycerides to peripheral tissues. This process requires specific proteins for proper assembly and secretion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following proteins is primarily responsible for the assembly of VLDL in the liver?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Albumin","Lipoprotein lipase","Apolipoprotein B-100","Apolipoprotein B-48","Apolipoprotein C-II"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApolipoprotein B-100\u003C/strong\u003E is a key structural protein necessary for the synthesis and secretion of very low-density lipoproteins (VLDL) in the liver. Each VLDL particle contains exactly one Apolipoprotein B-100 molecule, which is essential for its assembly and structural integrity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlbumin\u003C/strong\u003E transports free fatty acids in blood but is not involved in lipoprotein assembly\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipoprotein lipase\u003C/strong\u003E hydrolyses triglycerides within lipoproteins but does not participate in VLDL assembly\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApolipoprotein B-48\u003C/strong\u003E is produced exclusively in the intestine for chylomicron assembly\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApolipoprotein C-II\u003C/strong\u003E is a cofactor for lipoprotein lipase but is not involved in VLDL assembly\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of Apolipoprotein B-100 is absolutely required for VLDL synthesis and secretion from hepatocytes. Genetic defects in Apolipoprotein B-100 lead to impaired VLDL production and altered lipid metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Apolipoprotein B-100 is essential for the synthesis and secretion of very low-density lipoproteins (VLDL) in the liver.","VLDL is the main lipoprotein complex responsible for transporting triglycerides from the liver to peripheral tissues.","Apolipoprotein B-100 is specifically produced in the liver, while Apolipoprotein B-48 is produced in the intestine."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Lipid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Sep 1;13(9):a040576. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040576. PMID: 34470787; PMCID: PMC8411952","Wakil SJ, Abu-Elheiga LA. Fatty acid metabolism: target for metabolic syndrome. J Lipid Res. 2009 Apr;50 Suppl(Suppl):S138-43. doi: 10.1194/jlr.R800079-JLR200. Epub 2008 Dec 1. PMID: 19047759; PMCID: PMC2674721"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64063"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17873"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64063"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T15:01:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T15:05:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10587"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78720"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self